### Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe the problem.

It's quite common to have applications, which present lists of records in one or another way.
The examples in real life are endless - spanning from showing grid of images to a list of flat data records.

Many times, those records are much more than it makes sense to show on a single page. Some developers choose to have paged solutions, while others support infinite-scrolling, which behind the scenes would work in a similar fasion.

Currently, there is no native / standard way of supporting pagination, so every application developer will need to come up with their own solution. It would be great to provide a standard mechanism for doing this.

### Describe the solution you'd like

While this doesn't seem to be a big issue, and is relatively easy for developers to do, standardization would help as it hopefully will be utilized with other Microsoft services too.
The simplest form I can think of is introduction of these two APIs:

```csharp
public class PageRequest
{
  public int StartIndex {get;set;}
  public int Count {get;set;}
}

public class PagedResponse<T>
{
  public List<T> PageResults {get;set;}
  public bool MoreRecordsExist {get;set;}
}
```

The two simple types would allow developers to now standardize their APIs as follows:
(I assume even this could be optimized and made even nicer :) )
```csharp
public Task<PageResponse<T>> RetrieveResults(CustomRequest request, PageRequest request)
{
 // ...
}
```

### Additional context

As I've mentioned above, I don't have any specific proposal, this was just an example. But I want this issue to serve as a seed for thinking about standardizing the notation of exposing data paging capabilities through APIs.

